 of external genitalia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sequence of male sex differentiation begins with \u003Cstrong\u003Eexpression of the SRY gene\u003C/strong\u003E on the Y chromosome around week seven of development. This triggers the undifferentiated gonad to develop into testes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other events follow in this sequence:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelopment of seminiferous tubules\u003C/strong\u003E proceeds as the testes form\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of Leydig cells\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after SRY expression, leading to testosterone production\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegression of M\u00fcllerian ducts\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone from Sertoli cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelopment of external genitalia\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the final steps, requiring testosterone and dihydrotestosterone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWithout SRY gene expression, the default developmental pathway is female.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Sertoli-determining factor (SRY) gene on the Y chromosome triggers male sex differentiation","Anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone causes regression of the M\u00fcllerian ducts in male embryos","Testosterone from Leydig cells promotes development of male reproductive structures from Wolffian ducts"],"references":["Rey R, Josso N, Racine C. Sexual Differentiation. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc. [Updated 2020 May 27]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279001/","Human sexual differentiation [Internet]. www.gfmer.ch. [cited 2021 Jun 14]. Available from: https://www.gfm